abstract: The National Archives is letting millions of documents, including many related to immigrants’ rights, be destroyed or deleted.
snippet: The National Archives is letting millions of documents, including many related to immigrants’ rights, be destroyed or deleted.
lead_paragraph: Last month the National Archives found itself in the middle of a firestorm after it put a doctored photograph of the Women’s March on Washington on display. Even if the photo was not part of the National Archives’ own collection, the exhibit distorted history, and David S. Ferriero, the archivist of the United States, soon apologized.

abstract: The inside story of the president and Deutsche Bank, his lender of last resort.
snippet: The inside story of the president and Deutsche Bank, his lender of last resort.
lead_paragraph: One Day in early 2017, Mike Offit went to the Yale Club in Manhattan for a lunch hosted by a group called Business Executives for National Security. Offit, who has a craggy face and shoulder-­length hair, had spent much of his career in banking, but that had ended nearly two decades earlier. Since then, he had puttered around the outskirts of finance, dabbled in journalism and even published a novel about a pair of murders at a fictional German-­owned Wall Street bank that bore a striking resemblance to the one that he worked for until 1998: ­Deutsche Bank.

headline_main: Stephen Colbert Tells a Tale of 2 Kansas Cities

abstract: Increased security measures and how to pay for them have become an urgent issue for Jewish institutions.
snippet: Increased security measures and how to pay for them have become an urgent issue for Jewish institutions.
lead_paragraph: The East Midwood Jewish Center in Brooklyn needs $250,000 to replace its aging roof and another $250,000 to repair the water-damaged ceiling of its sanctuary, its director said. Then there is the aging boiler — the size of a small apartment — that has needed $20,000 worth of maintenance so far this winter.

abstract: A film starring Jodie Foster is airing. And President Trump delivers his third State of the Union Address.
snippet: A film starring Jodie Foster is airing. And President Trump delivers his third State of the Union Address.
lead_paragraph: CONTACT (1997) 7 p.m. on Ovation. Based on the 1985 science-fiction novel of the same title by Carl Sagan,  “Contact” yearns to bridge the gap between humanity and technological advancement. Jodie Foster plays Ellie Arroway, a scientist devoted to finding extraterrestrial life, who picks up a radio signal from another planet. This garners national attention, and as Ellie decodes the aliens’ message, she must protect her work from those trying to steal or discount it.  Ellie and a young minister named Palmer Joss (Matthew McConaughey) engage in a debate throughout over science and religion — and Palmer also becomes a love interest. “But try as it might to convey a humanist, mystical message and to equate the search for extraterrestrial life with religious faith,” Stephen Holden wrote in his review for The New York Times, “‘Contact’ is much more convincing when worshiping at the cold shrine of technology.”

headline_main: Coronavirus, Iowa, Brexit: Your Tuesday Briefing

abstract: Corrections that appeared in print on Tuesday, Feb. 4, 2020.
snippet: Corrections that appeared in print on Tuesday, Feb. 4, 2020.
lead_paragraph: Because of an editing error, an article on Friday about the helicopter crash that killed NBA star Kobe Bryant and eight others described incorrectly the minimum visibility requirements for flight under federal visual flight rules. They require a helicopter flying at low altitude in daylight to have at least a half-mile of visibility and visual reference to the ground, not at least three miles of visibility and a cloud ceiling no lower than 1,000 feet above the ground.
